// This file contains a "using the TANGO API for Igor Pro" tutorial. 
// It provides very detailed examples. A "must read" for any new comer to TANGO 
// under Igor Pro ! It also acts as a regression test for the binding itself. 
//
// However, it describes the "expert or advanced user" approach...
//
// Most users should first use the functions generated by "embedded code generator" 
// to access Tango devices. The latter provides a way to generate the Igor 
// interface of a specific device (i.e. for a specific device instance) or the 
// one of a device family (i.e. for a Tango class). The general rule is to 
// generate a "device interface" for devices having a single instance running 
// into the control system (e.g. monochromator device). Choose "class interface" 
// for devices for which sevral instances exist (e.g. motor devices). In the 
// latter case, you will have to specify the device name you want to communicate 
// with as first function paramater.  
//        
// How to generate some code?
// --------------------------
//
// 1. Open the Igor Data Browser (Data menu -> Data Browser)
//
// 2. Enable the Tango "expert or super user" option by setting the variable 
//    root:tango:common:xptm to 1 (i.e. true)
//
// 3. Open the Tango Browser (Tango menu -> Tango Browser)
// 
// 4. In the Tango Browser device list, right click on your "target device" 
//    and choose between "Generate Device Interface" or  "Generate Class 
//    Interface"
//
// 5. In the popup panel, enter the procedure file name (without .ipf extension), 
//    the functions prefix (recommended to avoid naming conflicts) . No need to 
//    change the target device name (just leave it as it is).
//
// 6. Click on the continue button then select the destination folder (i.e. the 
//    one in which the generated procedure will be saved).   
//
// 7. Done! The whole device (or class) interface is generated. Each functions 
//    comes with a commented example.  Just copy/paste/uncomment it to try the 
//    function you want to use.
